[normal]Passive level crossings
[normal]a.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The need for review of the safety of existing arrangements at crossings where the safety of users is dependent on them hearing a train horn sounded at a ‘whistle board’ (report 10/2012, 
[normal]Mexico
[normal], 
[normal]Penzance
[normal]: published June 2012).
[normal]Network Rail carried out a na
[normal]tional review to check the adequacy of the warning given to users at passive crossings.  It is also reviewing the position and adequacy of existing warning arrangements, and is developing alternative technical solutions to improve the warning given to user
[normal]s.  
[normal]The outcome of this review is awaited.
[normal]b.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The management of sub-standard sighting at footpath crossings (report 08/2010, 
[normal]Fairfield
[normal], Bedwyn: published May 2010).
[normal]Network Rail is carrying out trials with an audible warning device, which sounds at the cro
[normal]ssing as trains pass the ‘whistle boards’ in each direction.
[normal]The outcome of ongoing trials is awaited.
[normal]c.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Development of a standard national approach for the identification, marking and signing of the optimum decision point for pedestrians at footpath and user worked crossings (various reports including 10/2012, 
[normal]Mexico
[normal], 
[normal]Penzance
[normal]: published June 2012).
[normal]RSSB has
[normal] been commissioned to research issues concerning the safety of pedestrians at level crossings and safety of users at user worked level crossings.  RSSB has indicated it will bring forward and publish priority matters, and in particular the findings related
[normal] to ‘decision points’ of pedestrians.  
[normal]The RAIB believes that RSSB’s research will provide useful intelligence to both designers and risk assessors.  It is therefore important that this work is brought to a conclusion at the earliest opportunity.
[normal]d.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The ma
[normal]nagement of risk at user worked crossings with long waiting times due to absence of information to the signaller on the position of trains (report 14/2011, Sudbury: published August 2011).
[normal]Network Rail has developed, and is now testing, technology to enabl
[normal]e signallers to identify the location of a train in a long signal section.
[normal]The outcome of ongoing development work and trials is awaited.
[normal]Active level crossings
[normal]e.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Review of risk mitigation measures already identified in RSSB research related to the 
[normal]conspicuity of miniature stop lights currently used at footpath and user worked crossings (report 27/2012, Johnson’s: published December 2012).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]RAIB is awaiting information of the actions to be taken in response to this recommendation
[normal]f.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Engineering 
[normal]safeguards to prevent signallers raising barriers at level crossings before trains have passed clear (report 04/2011, Moreton-on-Lugg: published February 2011).
[normal]As a result of this recommendation Network Rail identified 97 crossings that are fitted with pr
[normal]otecting signals but without a sufficient engineered safeguard.  In a programme that is to be completed in February 2014, additional safety mitigation is being fitted to prevent signallers at these crossings erroneously opening the crossing to road traffic
[normal] while a train is still approaching.  
[normal]Having given priority to those crossings fitted with protecting signals Network Rail is now reviewing the options available for level crossings that do not have protecting signals.
