[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] All information 
[normal]in this submission 
[normal]concerning RAIB reports and recommendations relate only to the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s mainline railways. The RAIB has also investigated a number of accidents involving level crossings on 
[normal]h
[normal]eritage railways and 
[normal]t
[normal]ramways. 
[normal] Based on data provided by the 
[normal]RSSB
[normal]’s
[normal] Annual Safety Performance Report 2012-13.
[normal] The All Level C
[normal]rossing Risk Model (A
[normal]LCRM)
[normal] is a tool used by the industry that allows the level of risk to be estimated at an individual level crossing. 
[normal] The ‘sighting distance’ is the distance from the crossing at which approaching trains first come into view
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Passive crossings: no warning of a train’s approach is given other than by the train driver who may use the train horn. 
[normal] 
[normal]The onus is on the road user or pedestrian to determine whether or not it is safe to cross the line.
[normal] 
[normal] Instructions for proper use must 
[normal]be provided at each location, along with other appropriate signage.
[normal] Active crossings: the road vehicle or pedestrian is warned of the approach of a train through closure of gates or barriers and/or by stop lights and/or alarms.
[normal] 
[normal]Regulation 12 of the Rai
[normal]lways (Accident Investigation and Reporting) Regulations 2005
[normal] ORR Health and Safety Report 2013 (
[normal]http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/health-safety-report-2013.pdf
[normal])
[normal] In this investigation it was found that the train horn was not always audible to pedes
[normal]trians at the crossing
